Our education system never really taught people to look at the mainstream as having the correct information but providing it’s own interpretation of that information, so people wind up not trusting the information rather than not trusting that interpretation of the information.

They will jump straight from one incident of something that wasn’t wholly accurate to “the media is lying to us,” and from there to “the Illuminati are controlling the world” because they don’t know what they can believe any more.

RT @BreeThePhoenix: So, Thanksgiving storytime.  This evening, after Thanksgiving dinner, my family decided to play a game called "Scrawl".…

I hope the creators of Scrawl will forgive us, as we technically cheated and continued to play the game even when there WAS a fire.  There wasn't a whole lot we could do anyway, and it served to calm us all down.

As far as I'm aware, no one was harmed, and the fire department put it out within the hour and I don't believe any of the houses were damaged.  Still, I sure as hell didn't expect that clause of the rules to kick in.
We all go outside to check and, sure enough, just a few yards away, there is a sizeable brush fire, about the size of a house.  The closest I've ever been to a fire that size.

To everyone's surprise, it was my mother's neighbor (we were at my mother's house).  This neighbor informs us that there is a fire in the riverbed just outside the complex, and that it isn't an immediate danger, but that we should be aware just in case.

About twenty minutes pass, we've played one round of the game so far and are in the middle of a second when all of a sudden there's a knock on the door.  I guessed it was probably my sister-in-law, who had opted not to come because she wasn't feeling well.
Little did we know what was happening a few houses down at that moment.

Here we are all assuming this is like the Hugh Jackman rule from Cards Against Humanity, a silly rule that, unless you happen to be Hugh Jackman or a close friend of him will probably never be important.

I had to ask my brother if that was actually in there and he wasn't just throwing that in to be a goof, which is totally a possibility in this family.  He let me look at it to confirm that it does, indeed, say exactly that.

As I said, how the game is played isn't really important, but there was one rule that you do need to know.  According to the rules, the game is over when a player has a number of points equal to two more than the number of players "OR there is a fire."

How the game is played isn't particularly important, but just for a review for all of us, my brother decided to read the directions aloud.  Most of it was unsurprising to our little group of pseudo-veterans (it's really a game that is more fun if you're bad at it).

So, Thanksgiving storytime.  This evening, after Thanksgiving dinner, my family decided to play a game called "Scrawl".  It's a game we've played a number of times before and continue to play because it's something pretty much all of us can enjoy.
